I use to eat here when i was a kid in the 1970's when it was called Villa Gaudio's. Recently, I've been ordering food for delivery from this establishment during Covid-19 lock-down.  I must say the food here is excellent ! It's not just a great pizza place...(their Grandma slice is bigger than most i've seen)....this place has restaurant quality food and the portions are very large. Try their Eggplant Parmesan Hero, it's the best in town. (Most other pizza places i've tried it isn't as appetizing.)  Their tomato sauce taste the same as it did 30 or 40 years ago. If you love Italian food and don't want to spend alot of $$$, try this place. You can't go wrong !

I’m really upset that Gaudio’s plays games and tries to trick their customers!!!!  I went there on two previous occasions and ordered veal parmigiana and spaghetti eating it in their store. Being new to the neighborhood I was pleasantly surprised at the quality of the veal. It was soft and tender... a hallmark of good veal. Tonight I decided to order veal parm and spaghetti again only this time, I picked up the order and brought it home. After several bites it became quickly apparent that the quality of THIS veal was totally inferior. It was as tough as shoe leather and couldn’t cut it even with a steak knife!! And... I just wasted $20 and my time going there and picking up the food PLUS I STILL had no dinner!!!!  I felt totally betrayed by Gaudios. I’ve seen this game played before in many other pizza place/Italian restaurants in other neighborhoods. They save their highest quality veal to customers that dine in, knowing full well that they would complain and Gaudios would have to make another one if they were unhappy.  Gaudios counts on the fact that most take out customers would simply shrug it off and do nothing.  Well guess what? I hope everyone reading this review does NOT put 1$ in this store as they could care less about YOU.

A friendly gruffness and NY accents at the counter. Dependably good slices, with a thin crust that manages to stay crisped yet tender. The sauce was on the savory side, with little added in way of spices. When bringing me my mushroom (canned)-broccoli slice ($4.25), the man somehow knew that I'd want a fork and knife. With a "Here ya go, kiddo", he placed them on my table. Not too busy for tables at weekday lunch, Gaudio's does a lot of take-out and delivery. (The "small" pizza is 16", fyi.)
